snippet: Duluth, Minn., and Superior, Wis., are so close physically and culturally that they are known as the Twin Ports. But much began to change when Minnesota government went all Democratic and Wisconsin all Republican.
abstract: Neighboring cities of Duluth, Minn and Superior, Wis, once known as the Twin Ports, have become starkly different places since Democrats gained full dominance in Minnesota in 2013, and Republicans took over Wisconsin State Legislature in 2011; residents note big changes in their savings plans, job expectations, personal relationships and health insurance (Series: One-Party Rule).

byline.contributor: Nicholas Confessore contributed reporting from New York, and Kitty Bennett contributed research.

lead_paragraph: Duluth, Minn., and Superior, Wis., are so close physically and culturally that they are known as the Twin Ports. But much began to change when Minnesota government went all Democratic and Wisconsin all Republican.

headline.main: Twinned Cities Now Following Different Paths
headline.print_headline: Twinned Cities Now Following Different Paths
